  "story_title": "about",
  "review_text": "[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=extralarge; fonttype=bold; text=About Longbox Playback]\n\nLongbox Playback is a slow, deliberate walk through Marvel's early history - one issue at a time, in original publication order, staying as close as possible to what a reader in that moment would have experienced.&nbsp; It's part archive, part commentary, part archaeology, and part affectionate roast of the shared cultural fossil bed that accidentally built a universe.\n\nThe goal isn't to fix the past or reinterpret it with modern hindsight. It's to stay grounded in the moment of publication -- reacting to events as they happen, discovering surprises as they unfold, and letting retcons, reveals, and shocks land exactly when they arrive <i>in the original reading order</i>.&nbsp; (This includes annuals and occasional publication‑timing oddities, all placed in their actual release sequence -- using actual <i>on-sale</i> dates, <i>never</i> cover dates.)\n\nAny future knowledge that appears (usually in a Decoder Ring entry) is optional, lightweight, and <i>never the point</i>.&nbsp; The main experience is firmly rooted in [PAGE: scenario]:&nbsp; reading the comics as if the future hasn't happened yet.&nbsp; [DECODER_RING: Decoder Ring notes never change the review's verdict -- they live outside the Scenario.]\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= What Longbox Playback Is]\n\nLongbox Playback is:\n[HANG] * An archive of Marvel's history that stays true to the <b><i>publication order</i></b> above all else, each one consumed the way the original readers would have.\n[HANG] * A place to celebrate the charm, chaos, and accidental brilliance of early Marvel\n[HANG] * A continuity-respecting project that values <i>original</i> numbering and long-form history [SPAN: fontsize=small; fonttype=italic; text=(i.e. reboots are bad)]\n[HANG] * A project built around [PAGE: scenario] -- the constraint that keeps every review grounded in its original moment\n[HANG] * A home for structured reviews, metadata, and recurring features like the [PAGE: decoder-ring]\n[HANG] * A way to preserve the experience of reading these issues \"<i>within [PAGE: scenario]</i>\" -- the world as it existed when they were published\n\nIt's not a wiki, not a reboot, not a modern re-evaluation, and not a nostalgia blog.&nbsp; It's something stranger and more specific:&nbsp; a long-term <b>playback</b> of Marvel's earliest storytelling experiments, treated with equal parts respect and affectionate mockery.\n\n[SPAN: fontsize=small; text=For the guiding philosophy behind how this project reads and reviews comics, see] [PAGE: manifesto]\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= The Scenario]\n\n[PAGE: scenario] is the project's guiding constraint:\n[HANG] [SPAN: severity=info; fonttype=bold; text=read each issue as if you're living in the year it came out.]\n\nThat means:\n[HANG] * Issues are read and reviewed in the order they were published\n[BR] [SPAN: fontsize=small; text=(with some rare exceptions, always noted and explained briefly in the reviews)]\n[HANG] * No future knowledge in the main review  [SPAN: fontsize=small; text=(some of the <i>earliest</i> reviews cross the line a bit)]\n[HANG] * No spoilers for events that haven't been published yet\n[HANG] * No judging creators for decisions they couldn't foresee\n[HANG] * No assuming the Marvel Universe was inevitable or planned\n[HANG] * Letters pages are treated as real-time artifacts, not retroactive commentary\n\n[PAGE: scenario] keeps the reading experience grounded.&nbsp; Everything else -- the hindsight, the continuity echoes, the retcons -- lives in optional layers like the [PAGE: decoder-ring] page.\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= Why This Exists]\n\n[HANG0] * Because early Marvel is a miracle of improvisation.\n[HANG0] * Because the long tail of continuity is fascinating, sometimes hilarious, and often even confusing\n[HANG0] * Because reading these comics in order reveals patterns, experiments, and accidents you <i>cannot see</i> any other way [SPAN: fontsize=small; text=(especially if you focus on single titles)]\n\nLongbox Playback exists to:\n[HANG] * Capture the experience of reading these issues with fresh eyes\n[HANG] * Document the strange, wonderful evolution of characters and ideas\n[HANG] * Provide a structured, searchable archive for future readers (<i>still-to-come</i>)\n[HANG] * Celebrate the medium with a mix of sincerity, wry commentary, affectionate mockery\n[BR] [SPAN: fontsize=small; text=(and even the occasional \"How <i>Dare</i> You!\")]\n\nIt's a love letter to the messy, brilliant, physics-optional storytelling that built the Marvel Universe.\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= How to Use This Site]\n\nEach issue review includes:\n[HANG] * A summary box with the essentials\n[HANG] * An assigned \"verdict\" (which includes a grade using the same CGC scale everyone is familiar with)\n[HANG] * A spoil-light plot recap (closed by default, because you can get that <i>anywhere</i>)\n[HANG] * Deep commentary rooted in [PAGE: scenario]\n[HANG] * Optional meta-context via the [PAGE: decoder-ring]\n[HANG] * Side Notes, awards, recurring features, continuity notes, original letters page highlights, etc.\n[HANG] * Metadata for cross-referencing and future indexing (<i>still-to-come</i>)\n\nThere is a Monthly Summary available at the end of each \"publication month\" which notes key announcements, trends, weighted grades, highlights and lowlights of the month.\n\nAt the end of each publication year, a Year-In-Review breakdown is provided where awards are given out, callouts are made for the best and worst stories, panels, covers, letters, etc.&nbsp; And, because we know not everything went as it was perhaps intended, a <i>Trash Heap of the Year Award</i> winner is crowned (and that's not all - you can find the full list here: [PAGE: awards-index]).\n\nYou can read straight through chronologically (that means \"as originally published\"), dip into specific titles, or explore the meta-pages like the [PAGE: reading-order] or [PAGE: grading-rubric].\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= The Long Game]\n\nLongbox Playback is designed to grow over years, not weeks.&nbsp; As the archive expands, it becomes:\n[HANG] * A living record of Marvel's early creative evolution\n[HANG] * A continuity map built issue by issue (with a planned rollout of about 2-3 issues per week)\n[HANG] * A preservation of the lived reading experience -- not just the facts, but the feeling of discovery, and the wonder of what was still to come\n[HANG] * A reference for future readers who want to understand how the universe actually formed\n[HANG] * A curated, structured, and somewhat opinionated guide to the Silver and Bronze Age\n\nIt's a marathon, not a sprint:&nbsp; a longbox slowly unpacked, one comic at a time... exactly as a reader would have had to experience them every month after visiting the drug store and turning the spinner rack."
}